Load the the library and dplyr for data manipulation.

library(eventsObserveR)
library(dplyr)

There are a set of sample event observations provided in the library

head(sample_events_data)
##                  time event_type radius   color place_id    station
## 1 2014-11-11 19:02:25     spider      5 #460B5E        0 Station_01
## 2 2014-11-12 04:41:15     jerboa      5 #481568        0 Station_01

## 4             2 polar bear
## 5             2 polar bear
## 6             3  eagle owl

These can be displayed in an eventsObserver viewer by specifying just the place.key as the column name station. Unique places are distributed round a circle in the order that they first appear in the place.key column.

eventsObserveR(events = sample_events_data,
               place.key = "station")

Events occur at specific coordinates

Make a legend

legend.df <- sample_events_data %>%
  select(event_type, color, event_type_id) %>%
  rename(description = event_type) %>%
  unique()
## Warning in combine_vars(vars, ind_list): '.Random.seed' is not an integer
## vector but of type 'NULL', so ignored
head(sample_locations_data)
## # A tibble: 6  6
##       x     y    id color radius     title
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <chr>  <dbl>     <chr>
## 1    25    90     0  pink     10 Station 1
## 2    62    25     1  pink     10 Station 2
## 3    72    88     2  pink     10 Station 3
## 4    60    69     3  pink     10 Station 4
## 5    12    55     4  pink     10 Station 5
## 6    61    19     5  pink     10 Station 6
eventsObserveR(events = sample_events_data, 
               place.key = "station",
               places = sample_locations_data,
               legend = legend.df,
               legend.columns = 2,
               shape.type = "circle",
               size = list(
                 view.width = 1040,
                 view.height = 720,
                 interface.width = 1200, 
                 interface.height = 900))
